<p><b>Robert James "Bob" Shiller</b> (born March 29, 1946<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>) is an <a href="/wiki/United_States" title="United States">American</a> economist, academic, and best-selling author. He currently serves as the <a href="/wiki/Arthur_M._Okun" title="Arthur M. Okun" class="mw-redirect">Arthur M. Okun</a> Professor of Economics at <a href="/wiki/Yale_University" title="Yale University">Yale University</a> and is a Fellow at the Yale International Center for Finance, <a href="/wiki/Yale_School_of_Management" title="Yale School of Management">Yale School of Management</a>. Shiller has been a <a href="/wiki/Research" title="Research">research</a> associate of the <a href="/wiki/National_Bureau_of_Economic_Research" title="National Bureau of Economic Research">National Bureau of Economic Research</a> (NBER) since 1980, was Vice President of the <a href="/wiki/American_Economic_Association" title="American Economic Association">American Economic Association</a> in 2005, and President of the Eastern Economic Association for 2006-2007. He is also the founder and chief economist of the investment management firm MacroMarkets LLC.</p>
<p>Shiller is ranked among the 100 most influential economists of the world.<sup id="cite_ref-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
